by the chair — and a guilty verdict requires
a simple majority. The only elections hear-
ing this year took place, Brown said, when
then-Board member Alex Murdoch was
accused of being a member of a Forbes and
Fifth Facebook group, violating an elec-
tions code rule that forbids sitting mem-
bers of SGB from supporting or campaign-
ing for any candidates running to replace
them. The case was dropped because the
defense argued the evidence was found
illegally.

Processing so many infractions accord-
ing to those steps could have meant op-
pressive inconvenience and assault to “the
sanity of candidates,” Brown said.

“Nobody wanted to have the hearings.
A lot of time it became too much of a dis-
traction,” she said, referring speciﬁcally
to “petty” infractions such as incorrectly
hung posters.

“A poster hanging on a window — all
of the candidates have to come in,” Brown
said, describing the inconvenience that
would have been caused by holding a hear-
ing for every infraction.

The elections code addresses several
kinds of campaign behavior. The rules most
commonly invoked by campaigns ﬁling
infractions concern the paper campaigning
period — which usually begins a few days
before the election — during which the
campaigns can distribute posters around
campus. The code bars campaigns from

placing posters on glass doors and from

obstructing opponents’ ﬂiers.

But not all infractions involved a poster
hanging on a window.

“There’s a big difference between a
group performing on behalf of a group 
[when] they did not have an endorsement,
or if someone hangs a poster on awindow,”
Brown said. .

But if infractions truly varied in sever-
ity, their treatment in the past election did
not reﬂect it. ‘

Brown said that drawing lines between
different types of infractions “seems very
arbitrary to me. How do we determine
what’s below the line and what’s above
the line?”

Brown argues that her discretionary
powers, granted to her by elections code
clause 104.04 so she can “ensure a fair,

honest and efﬁcient election,” allowed her
to condone infraction withdrawals regard-
less of severity. 7

“It falls under discretion and prec-
edent,” she said. “Infractions had been
allowed to be withdrawn before.”

