WOMEN’S BASKETBALL

Dave Uhrmacher
Staff W riter

The Pitt women’s basketball team will host
defending national champion and currently
No. 2-ranked Notre Dame on Wednesday
night in what could be the Panthers’ toughest
test all season.

Coming off a 74-65 loss on Saturday to
Marquette, a game in which the Panthers
(9-8, 0-3 Big East) showed their ability to
compete in the Big East, Pitt looks to break
a 22-game Big East conference losing streak
against the Irish at 7 p.m. at the Petersen
Events Center.

With such a young lineup, not much is
expected of this Pitt squad against the pow-
erhouse Fighting Irish, but sophomore for-
ward Cora McManus, coming off a 15-point
performance in the loss to Marquette, looks
at this game as a wonderful opportunity for
the Panthers.

“We are going to play hard, we have noth-
ing to lose going into this game,” she said. “I
don’t care who we are playing, we are going
to go out there with no fear.”

McManus will be joined in the frontcourt
by junior forward Asia Logan, who leads
the team in scoring (15.5 points per game)
but has struggled her past two games, only
managing to shoot 5-for-25 (20 percent)
from the ﬁeld. Getting Logan back on track
will be key for the Panthers if they want to
pull off the upset victory.

Notre Dame (15-1, 4-0 Big East) is led
by three—time All-American and arguably
the best point guard in the country, senior
Skylar Diggins.Junior guard Kayla McBride,

an Erie, Pa., native who attended Villa Maria
Academy, ranks second on the team in scor-
ing, behind Diggins. Both players average
approximately 15 points per game and the
Irish as a whole average 83 points per game,
emerging victorious by an average 25-point
margin.

Pitt head coach Agnus Berenato is eager
to be tested against such a strong squad at
home.

“I’m glad Notre Dame is coming to our
house,” she said. “We like playing at home,
and they are a great‘ team. They are No. 2
in the nation. They won the national title
game last year. Just last week they went in
and beat No. 1 Connecticut at their house.”

The only loss for the Irish this season
came back on Dec. 5, when they lost 73-61
to currently No. 1-ranked Baylor at home.

‘ Notre Dame sophomore guard and for-
mer Pittsburgh Post-Gazette Athlete of the
Year Madison Cable, a Mt. Lebanon gradu-
ate, travels back to Pittsburgh for the ﬁrst
time in her collegiate career. She is averaging
4.2 points per game off the bench for head
coach Muffet McGraw.

The Panthers, who start two freshmen,
two sophomores and ajunior, will need to do
every little thing right to stay with the Irish.

Although her team lost by an incredible
76 points against Notre Dame last season,
Berenato remains optimistic that this year’s
clash with the Irish will be different.

“As a player and as a coach, this matchup
is what dreams are made of,” Berenato said.
“You dream about playing the big team. They
are very, very good, but at the same time, we
lace up our sneakers just like they do. It is
ﬁve girls against ﬁve girls.” ﬂ

