Pitt drops match against national powerhouse Oklahoma State

Dustin Gabler
Senior Staff Writer

Despite its best performances at the lower
weight classes all season, the No. 17 Pitt
wrestling team fell to No. 2 Oklahoma
State 26-14 on Sunday.

The Cowboys’ fans packed the Gallagh-
er-Iba Arena in Stillwater, Okla., to cheer
on their wrestlers, and the atmosphere
helped get the Panthers excited for one
of their biggest matches of the season.

“The atmosphere at Oklahoma State
was great,” Pitt’s Shelton Mack said. “The
fans were really into the match, so it made
it that much easier to get ﬁred up. It’s hard
to be in a place like that and not want to
wrestle your absolute best.”

Mack, ranked 17th by InterMat Wres-

tling, has had an up-and-down season
with many close matches.

The 133-pounder was preparing for
a top matchup against Oklahoma State’s
No. 5 Jon Morrison, but instead matched
up with Tyler Dorrell.

After Pitt’s Derrick Nelson was pinned
in the 125-pound match, Mack needed a
big performance, and he came up with
one.

The junior came through with a 13-6
decision for the Panthers with a big ﬁve-
point third period after a takedown, two
near-fall points and an escape.

At 141 pounds, Pitt’s Travis Shaffer
turned in a dominating performance with
a 15-0 technical fall. Shaffer appeared to
have his opponent,]ulian Feikert, pinned
several times, but the referee disagreed.

The loss to Bloomsburg two weeks ago
sparked a lot of the upperclassmen to call
for a change in the team’s approach. Sev-
eral Pitt wrestlers performed much better,
especially considering the higher-quality
competition.

“I was excited about the whole match.
Some people really stepped up,” said Matt
Wilps, the Panthers’ highest-ranked wres-
tler.

With Shaffer’s win, Pitt led the nation-
al-championship-contending Cowboys,
8-6. It would be the last time the Panthers
led in the match.

Oklahoma State’s final five wrestlers
are all ranked and many presented the
Panthers’ wrestlers with their toughest
match of the season.

Pitt’s Ronnie Garbinsky matched up

against top-ranked Jordan Oliver at 149
pounds. Oliver led Garbinsky 2-0 heading
into the third period and then exploded.
The No. 1 wrestler at this weight class hit
Garbinsky with ﬁvetakedowns, running
the ﬁnal score up to 14-4. A

No. 10 Alex Dieringer earned a take-
down and three near-fall points on Pitt’s
Donnie Tasser at 157 pounds and held onto
that lead for an 8-2 victory.

In a matchup of ranked wrestlers, No.
3 Tyler Caldwell of Oklahoma State de-
feated No. 13 Tyler Wilps. Caldwell led
5-0 heading into the ﬁnal period. After
Wilps escaped, his attempts at a takedown
of his own all proved unsuccessful and
he lost 5-1.

